3.6 Control Structures
R includes standard programming tools such as conditionals and loops.

3.6.1 If statement
x &lt;- -999
if (x == -999) {
  x &lt;- NA
}
print(x)
Comparison with numbers that have decimal expansions can be tricky.
0.1 == 0.3 / 3
This returns FALSE because of floating-point precision. Computers cannot represent most decimals exactly, so calculations like 0.3 / 3 produce a number very close to, but not exactly, 0.1. To compare numbers safely, use a tolerance with all.equal():
all.equal(0.1, 0.3 / 3)
```r
x &lt;- 10
if (x &gt; 5) {
  print("x is greater than 5")
} else {
  print("x is not greater than 5")
}


3.6.2 For loop
for (i in 1:3) {
  print(i^2)
}


3.6.3 While loop
count &lt;- 1
while (count &lt;= 3) {
  print(count)
  count &lt;- count + 1
}
Exercise: Write a loop that sums the numbers from 1 to 10, and use an if-statement to check if the sum is greater than 50.
